Elon Musk has been forced to resign as Tesla's board chairman
The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission and Tesla founder Elon Musk have settled their fraud case.
This is reported by CNBC News.
According to the network, Musk will have to step down as Tesla's board chairman as part of the deal.
The commission allowed Musk to remain Tesla's CEO.
The Tesla founder will also have to pay an administrative fine of $20 million.
The same amount will be charged to Tesla.
The money will be distributed among the affected investors.
In addition, the company must appoint two independent directors.
Elon Musk is an American businessman who is listed among the 50 richest people on the planet by Forbes magazine.
He is the CEO of SpaceX, the Neuralink neurotechnology company, and the developer of the Tesla electric car, as well as the co-founder of Paypal.
The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission has previously sued Tesla CEO Elon Musk over his tweet about a possible buy-out.
Last month, Musk announced plans to take Tesla private and buy all of its shares on the stock exchange at a fixed price of $420.
The $420 price tag was set allegedly "because of the significance of this number in the marijuana culture", Bloomberg reported earlier, citing the commission's security department co-director, Stephen Paikin.
At the same time, Elon Musk subsequently abandoned his plans to buy back the shares.
Commenting on the lawsuit filed against him by the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, the businessman said he found the fraud charges unfounded, adding that he was very disappointed and saddened by the claims.
"Honesty is the most important value in my life, and the facts will prove that I have not violated it in any way", the businessman told CNBC in an interview.
In August, a group of Tesla shareholders filed a class action lawsuit against Musk, complaining of financial losses.
The plaintiffs claimed that the businessman's posts had cost them.
In particular, one shareholder claimed that the businessman's tweets were misleading, forcing Tesla stock sellers to buy securities at artificially inflated prices to cover their positions.
Other plaintiffs also noted that Elon Musk's careless statements led to sharp fluctuations in the course.
In September, Elon Musk also accused the head of research company Citron Research of stock fraud.
Meanwhile, if Musk couldn't settle his dispute with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, he could face removal from the company's board and even prison.
This was stated by former commission chairman Harvey Pitt, in particular, to CNBC.
