On September 30, 1928, exactly 90 years ago, British bacteriologist Alexander Fleming announced an unprecedented discovery.
The discovery of penicillin marked the beginning of the modern antibiotic era, brought Fleming worldwide fame and made him a Nobel laureate.
By the way, extracting penicillin from mould was not Fleming's first discovery.
A few years earlier, he had a cold and had sown mucus from his nose on a Petri dish (a glass lid used to test bacteria) and found that the bacteria had been destroyed in a few days.
They also discovered penicillin almost by accident.
Fleming's name was included in the list of 100 most outstanding personalities in human history.
His discovery, according to many scientists, changed the course of history.
With the help of penicillin, medicine has begun to deal with most of the ancient diseases that were previously thought to be incurable - tuberculosis, syphilis, gangrene...
When Fleming arrived in the French capital in 1945, shortly after receiving the Nobel Prize, the Paris newspapers reported: "He has done more than a dozen divisions for the defeat of fascism and the liberation of France".
