Kosachev: Russia was virtually absent at the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly
The head of the Federation Council's committee on international affairs, Konstantin Kosachev, considers the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly to be a success for Russia and does not rule out that it could become a turning point in the perception of Russia as an integral participant in solving global world problems.
"The uniqueness of this 73rd session, in my opinion, is that the rhetoric we've become almost accustomed to in recent years about Russia has now been a bit more muted", the senator said in an interview published Sunday by the Russian newspaper.
He explained that in previous years, Russia was often "identified as one of the three main threats to humanity, along with Ebola, climate change or terrorism, Russia was in this list, at least in the exposition of a group of Western countries, which was quite unanimous on this matter".
At the 73rd session, Kosachev stressed, "the topic of Russia in a negative way was almost absent".
"If you look at the US president, the French president, the German foreign minister, I'm not looking at Ukraine, Georgia, or the British, at least the chorus wasn't exactly right", the politician said, noting that Russia "was no longer a wall to be trained on with a tennis ball".
The head of the relevant committee of the Fed does not rule out that this indicates a trend that, in his opinion, "will distinguish the current session [of the UN General Assembly], although in full this trend may be manifested in a year, two, three".
"I do not exclude that this session could be a turning point in some sense", Kosachev said, explaining that "there are too many examples of how Russia's involvement can move forward in international affairs".
He cited the situation in Syria, around Iran and North Korea as examples.
"Unfortunately, it is not Ukraine, but I have no doubt that the Russian vision of the Ukrainian crisis will also be in demand over time", the parliamentarian added.
This is due to the fact, he believes, that there is an "adequate, healthy perception of Russia as not just a possible - an integral participant in solving the global problems of today".
"I don't want to be wrong, but I have a feeling that we are passing a point somewhere where the movement is no longer going to be a backward movement, it will be a forward movement", he added.
Another "interesting and important feeling" in this context, Kosachev called "a request for the Russian vision of how the modern world should develop".
"I attended many meetings of the head of the Russian delegation [at the session of the General Assembly] the Minister of Foreign Affairs Sergei Lavrov, I held my own meetings, and I was very pleased to see that if a year or two or five years ago, Russian opinion, Russian vision of what is happening in the world, in general, nobody was interested, then the situation is different now", the Chairman of the Fed Committee said.
He believes that this is because "the so-called new liberal order, which is the West, has no answers to the questions of how to solve the world's problems because of the obvious lack of ideas in the global space, lack of ideas about how to solve the problems of the Middle East, the problems of terrorism, the problems of nuclear non-proliferation, the problems of migration".
"And here the request for Russian vision is becoming more and more obvious", - said Kosachev, stressing that he considers in this sense "the current session successful for the work of the Russian delegation, successful for Russia".
