AdG became the second most popular in Germany
The anti-immigrant Alternative for Germany is hitting another popularity record, and Angela Merkel's ratings are falling.
It seems that the German people are getting seriously tired of Angela Merkel's immigration policies, which have made the country a desirable destination for millions of refugees from the Middle East.
The most obvious evidence of this is the latest polls, which show the anti-immigrant party "Alternative for Germany" becoming more popular, while the positions of the ruling bloc of Merkel and Seehofer are weakening.
This week, the ADG broke another record, climbing to second place in the popularity rankings.
The right-wing conservatives, with 17 percent of the vote, have managed to overtake the Social Democrats, who have about 16 percent.
The one-percent gap can be attributed to a statistical error, but it is also worth noting that the ADG, which was created in 2013 by a small group of Eurosceptic economists, has managed to become a serious political force.
The overall lead is still held by the ruling bloc of the Christian Democratic Union/CDU, which has about 30 percent.
However, there is a tendency to lose points here - back in April, support for Angela Merkel's bloc was four percentage points higher.
The personal rating of the German chancellor, who is leading the German government for the fourth consecutive term, is also declining.
Today, 48 percent of Germans support Angela Merkel, down 7 percent from last year.
We should add that the "greens" (15%), the left (11%) and the liberals (10%) followed the Social Democrats.
The evolution of the Alternatives.
The Alternative for Germany party was founded in September 2012 on the basis of the Alternative Choice 2013 group, which included members of the Christian Democratic Union.
The group initially opposed the government's policy, but at first it focused on economic issues, including the euro and EU cooperation.
The group opposed Germany's "sponsorship" of the EU's weak economies, and did not rule out the possibility of a return to the German mark and a complete exit of the country from the European Union.
As the immigration crisis deepened, the political platform of the ADG expanded.
In 2013, the group became a full-fledged party, which took over the niche of Eurosceptics and began to harshly criticize the government for its failed immigration policy.
In the last parliamentary elections in 2017, the AdG managed to break into the Bundestag for the first time, winning 94 seats (out of 709).
Two representatives of Alternative for Germany won seats in the European Parliament.
