Macedonian opposition leader refuses to vote in referendum
In Macedonia, on Sunday, September 30, a referendum is held on the issue of the intergovernmental agreement with Greece on renaming the Republic of Macedonia.
Citizens are asked to answer one question: "Do you support EU and NATO membership by accepting the agreement between the Republic of Macedonia and the Greek Republic?"
However, the leader of the leading opposition party "Internal Macedonian Revolutionary Organization - Democratic Party for Macedonian National Unity" (VMRO-DPMNE) Christiane Mitzkowski has stated that he will not vote in the referendum.
Party spokesman Naum Stoilkovsky explained that Mitskowski decided to abstain from voting to express his disagreement with the agreement, which he considers "pernicious".
According to the press secretary, the current referendum is about changing the name of the country and nothing more, while the strategic goal of the party is to achieve membership in NATO and the EU.
A week ago, the president of Macedonia, Georgi Ivanov, refused to participate in the September 30 referendum.
He explained that the name for the country he chose 27 years ago at the referendum on independence. The Macedonian leader considers the renaming of the country a negative factor.
"A new semi-sovereign state with a new name is being created", Ivanov noted.
The agreement on the new official name of the former Yugoslav republic - the Republic of Northern Macedonia - was signed by the foreign ministers of Macedonia and Greece on June 17 this year during a solemn ceremony on the shore of Prespa Lake, which marks the border between the two countries.
This treaty should resolve the long-standing dispute over the country's name, as well as Skopje's path to NATO and the EU, TASS reminds.
